":"1370–1447","1385–1433":"1385–1433","1387–Male":"1387–Overleden","1389–Female":"1389–Overleden","1346–Male":"1346–Overleden","1350–Female":"1350–Overleden","about 1370":"circa 1370","1385":"1385","20 May 1447":"20 mei 1447","1350":"1350","1371":"1371","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1447":"1447","1346":"1346","1433":"1433","1389":"1389","1387":"1387","about 1389":"circa 1389","about 1387":"circa 1387","Wells next the Sea, Norfolk, England":"Wells next the Sea, Norfolk, England","Swaffham, Norfolk, Inglaterra, Reino Unido, England":"Swaffham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France":"Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1370–20 May 1447":"about 1370–20 May 1447","1370–1447":"1370–1447","1385–1433":"1385–1433","1387–Male":"1387–Deceased","1389–Female":"1389–Deceased","1346–Male":"1346–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","1385":"1385","20 May 1447":"20 May 1447","1350":"1350","1371":"1371","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1447":"1447","1346":"1346","1433":"1433","1389":"1389","1387":"1387","about 1389":"about 1389","about 1387":"about 1387","Wells next the Sea, Norfolk, England":"Wells next the Sea, Norfolk, England","Swaffham, Norfolk, Inglaterra, Reino Unido, England":"Swaffham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France":"Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Kyriell was born about 1370, in Wells next the Sea, Norfolk, England, her father, Thomas Kyreill, was 25 and her mother, Mrs. Thomas Keyreill, was 21. She married Sir John Stewart II. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died on 20 May 1447, in Calais, Dordogne, Aquitaine, France, at the age of 78."},"et":{"about 1370–20 May 1447":"umbes 1370–20. mai 1447","1370–1447":"1370–1447","1385–1433":"1385–1433","1387–Male":"1387–Surnud","1389–Female":"13